post_text:
NVS Cheerleading selling Driveway Art!

The Nodaway Valley varsity football/basketball cheerleaders are selling driveway art to raise funds for new uniforms, state competition fees, honor squad and other expenses. They are planning to make this an annual fundraiser and hope that the communities will love showing their Wolverine Pride!

The cost this first year is $25 and next year it will be $25 for a new one or $15 to refresh one that is purchased this year. The team will be out painting the driveway art the weekend of August 29 and September 19. To sign up and purchase, please contact cheer sponsor Crystal Ruth at crystal.ruth@nodawayvalley.org or by calling 515-250-8834.

Thank you for your support!

August 21, 2020 - On Friday night at SWV, a 17-year-old school record was broken!

Caelen DeVault, junior, broke the school record for receptions in a game. The old record was held by Matthew Mitchell (Class of 2004) with 10 in 2003. Caelen had 11 v SWV.

Congratulations, Caelen! Here is one of his 11 catches on the night.
text:
August 21, 2020 - On Friday night at SWV, a 17-year-old school record was broken!

Caelen DeVault, junior, broke the school record for receptions in a game. The old record was held by Matthew Mitchell (Class of 2004) with 10 in 2003. Caelen had 11 v SWV.

Congratulations, Caelen! Here is one of his 11 catches on the night.

If you qualified for Free & Reduced School Meals in 2019-2020, please use this link (https://dhs.iowa.gov/P-EBT_FAQ_Page) for information on the P-EBT card.

Here are some key points:

‚Ä¢ Every child enrolled in the Free & Reduced Lunch Program will receive $307.80.
‚Ä¢ If you already receive Food Assistance, the $307.80 for each child will be added to your card on July 15, 2020.
‚Ä¢ If you do not receive Food Assistance, you will receive an envelope in the mail addressed to your child with a Texas return address. A card will be inside the envelope with the $307.80 uploaded on it. Each child will receive their own card in a separate envelope for parents/guardians to use.
‚Ä¢ If you have questions, please call this DHS phone number 1-877-347-5678 from 8 a.m. ‚Äì 4:30 p.m. Monday ‚Äì Friday.

Again, please visit https://dhs.iowa.gov/P-EBT_FAQ_Page for more information.

Janell Stender
Food Service Director

The Technology Access Survey will close at 11:59 p.m. on Wednesday, June 24. Here is the link:

Survey link: http://bit.ly/iowatechsurvey

The survey should take no longer than five minutes to complete and will help the state to better understand the specific technology needs of PK-12 and postsecondary learners. The information will help us determine how to best use the Governor‚Äôs Emergency Education Relief (GEER), which focuses on providing and expanding broadband access and improving access to technology in other ways.

Congratulations!

-Mrs. Britten

post_text:
April 10, 2020 - In these unprecedented times comes an unconventional signing site.

Summerset No. 3 country school, two miles north of Fontanelle, with the Baudler cow/calf farm in the background, became the signing site for Nodaway Valley's senior Joshua Baudler.

Joshua signed his letter of intent to run both cross country and track and field at Southwestern Community College located in Creston.

Joshua was this past year's IHSAA Class 1-A Individual State Champion in Cross Country.

In the 2018-19 school year Josh was the Class 1-A State Runner-up in cross country, and finished second in the 3200 and third in the 1600 at the State Track Meet as a Junior.

He will major in Ag Business and Livestock Production.

Congratulations, Joshua!

B

Seated: Darla Baudler, Josh Baudler, John Baudler; Back: Jodi Baudler, Nodaway Valley Coach Darrell Burmeister, Jacob Baudler

Images courtesy of Mr. Dickinson.

post_text: Students and Families - Nodaway Valley Schools will be in session Monday, March 16, on a normal schedule. Per the Governor's recommendation the district will shut down for a four-week period beginning Tuesday, March 17. As of now, we will resume classes Monday, April 13. This could change with further developments. Please have students bring an additional bag and plan on taking home all personal items and be prepared to turn in all school owned textbooks. Students who have school issued Chromebooks will be able to keep their computers. All athletes participating in spring activities will report to practices tomorrow afternoon to assist in the putting away of equipment and cleaning out their athletic lockers. The state associations (IAHSAA, IGHSAU, etc.) will provide further guidance on the status of spring activities tomorrow. Any students in possession of any school owned uniforms are to bring them and turn them in to their coaches tomorrow as well. All personal items must be taken home. -Superintendent Paul Croghan

post_text:
The Warren Cultural Center is opening an exhibit, "Windows to the Past Open Doors to the Future," a project created by Nodaway Valley Elementary School 4th grade students. The opening reception is Saturday, March 7 from 10:00 - 1:00, with the exhibit open daily in the Warren Cultural Center lobby from 8:00 am - 4:00 pm and Saturdays 11 am - 3:00 pm.

Based on a curriculum unit titled "My Hometown," students participated in a walking tour of Greenfield's Public Square Historic District, then adopted a building to research, then wrote poetry, created dioramas, mobiles, games, and visited with local historians about their favorite buildings. Be sure to stop by the Warren Cultural Center gallery from March 7 to March 28 to see this creative children's art and history exhibit about Greenfield's Historic District.

Friday, March 6 - Nearly half of the NVHS student body participated in our first annual National Day of Unplugging! Great Job, students!
52% Sophomores
51% Juniors
46% Seniors
40% Freshmen
Students turned their phones in at 8:25 and were able to pick them up at 3:25.

Be sure to watch NVTV on Monday to see how students survived the day without their cell phones!

From Mr. Miller...
Studies have shown that 8/10 students who participate in a digital detox will continue to "detox" from their phones following this event.

Stress and anxiety levels decrease following a digital detox. This includes not just teenagers but also ADULTS!

A UCLA study found that pre-teens who were deprived of screens for 5 days through a digital detox were much better at reading people‚Äôs emotions (non-verbal skills) than children who continued using screens.

HAPPY (UNPLUGGED) FRIDAY!

Images courtesy of Mrs. Hubenka (who turned in her phone after these photos)!

Nodaway Valley has three teams in the Ten Week Live Healthy Iowa Challenge‚Äîan elementary, a middle school/high school and a high school team. Over the course of ten weeks, teams track activity minutes and/or weight loss through the Live Healthy Iowa website. This simple challenge provides Iowans an opportunity to improve their health while engaging in fun, friendly competition.

Nurse DeVault selects winners based on activity time/weight loss from each group. This week the winner was drawn for highest percent of weight loss. The top three from each team are Norma McCutchan, Dawn Witt, and Chelsea Davis. Congrats to all three of you...and the winner of a $10 Fareway gift card is Norma McCutchan!

Nodaway Valley Elementary is implementing the Positive Behavior Interventions and Supports program as a building-wide system to teach behavior expectations and acknowledge those students who demonstrate such expectations. This system is meant to reinforce the positive behaviors displayed by students, both as individuals and as a classroom as a whole. Acknowledgement comes in the way of ‚ÄúPAWsome‚Äù tickets and ‚ÄúWonderful Wolverine‚Äù coupons being awarded to individual students. These tickets and coupons can be redeemed for various incentives, also known as reinforcers.

You can learn more here (http://www.nodawayvalley.org/pbis) and view the weekly winners of ‚ÄúPAWsome‚Äù tickets and ‚ÄúWonderful Wolverine‚Äù coupons.

The Nodaway Valley Elementary Staff

Slides designed each week by NVHS senior Baylie Lund.

Nodaway Valley has three teams in the Ten Week Live Healthy Iowa Challenge‚Äîan elementary, a middle school/high school and a high school team. Over the course of ten weeks, teams track activity minutes and/or weight loss through the Live Healthy Iowa website (https://www.livehealthyiowa.org/). This simple challenge provides Iowans an opportunity to improve their health while engaging in fun, friendly competition.

Nurse DeVault selects winners based on activity time/weight loss from each group. In the first round Peggy Keuning, Joceline Vry and Jane Woodside had top activity minutes in each group and Mrs. Woodside was the lucky winner of the Subway card from the random drawing.

ES Team Average - 688 minutes
HS Team Average - 608 minutes
MS/HS Combo Team Average - 448 minutes

‚ÄìNurse Amy DeVault
